<!-- MAIN CONTENT -->
<div class="card">
<div class="card-header">
<div class="card-icon">üî¢</div>
<h2>What Is a Mole?</h2>
</div>

<p>
The <strong>mole</strong> is the SI unit for amount of substance. One mole is defined as exactly \(6.022 \times 10^{23}\) elementary entities (atoms, molecules, ions, or particles). This number is called <strong>Avogadro's number</strong> (\(N_A\)).
</p>

<div class="formula-box">
1 mole = \(6.022 \times 10^{23}\) particles
</div>

<p>
The mole connects the microscopic world (individual atoms) to the macroscopic world (grams we can measure). Just as "dozen" means 12, "mole" means \(6.022 \times 10^{23}\).
</p>

<div class="info-box">
<strong>Why 6.022 √ó 10¬≤¬≥?</strong><br>
This number was chosen so that one mole of carbon-12 atoms has a mass of exactly 12 grams. It bridges atomic mass units (amu) to grams: 1 amu √ó \(N_A\) = 1 g/mol.
</div>

<h3>The Magnitude of a Mole</h3>

<p>
Avogadro's number is incomprehensibly large. Consider these comparisons:
</p>

<div class="table-wrap">
<table>
<tr>
<th>Comparison</th>
<th>Illustration</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>If you had a mole of rice grains</td>
<td>It would cover the Earth's surface to a depth of ~75 meters</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>If you counted 1 particle per second</td>
<td>It would take ~19 trillion years (longer than the age of the universe)</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>If a mole of basketballs</td>
<td>They would fill the volume of Earth many times over</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>A mole of dollars</td>
<td>Would give every person on Earth ~$80 trillion</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<div class="highlight-box">
<strong>‚ö†Ô∏è Critical for HSC:</strong> Always use \(N_A = 6.022 \times 10^{23}\) (4 significant figures) unless the question specifies otherwise. Using \(6.02 \times 10^{23}\) loses precision and may cost marks.
</div>
</div>

<div class="card">
<div class="card-header">
<div class="card-icon">üîÑ</div>
<h2>The Mole Conversion Triangle</h2>
</div>

<p>
The mole sits at the center of all quantitative chemistry calculations. You must be fluent in three conversions:
</p>

<div class="flowchart">
                Number of Particles (N)
                        ‚Üë
                        | √∑ N‚Çê
                        |
                    MOLES (n)
                        |
                        | √ó MM
                        ‚Üì
                    MASS (m)

<strong>Key Relationships:</strong>
n = N / N‚Çê          (moles = particles √∑ Avogadro's number)
N = n √ó N‚Çê          (particles = moles √ó Avogadro's number)
m = n √ó MM          (mass = moles √ó molar mass)
n = m / MM          (moles = mass √∑ molar mass)
</div>

<h3>Worked Example 1: Particles to Moles</h3>

<div class="info-box">
<strong>Question:</strong> How many moles are in \(1.806 \times 10^{24}\) water molecules?<br><br>

<strong>Solution:</strong><br>
<strong>Given:</strong> \(N = 1.806 \times 10^{24}\) molecules<br>
<strong>Find:</strong> \(n = ?\) mol<br>
<strong>Formula:</strong> \(n = \frac{N}{N_A}\)<br><br>

\[n = \frac{1.806 \times 10^{24}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} = 3.000 \text{ mol}\]<br>

<strong>Answer:</strong> 3.000 mol (4 sig figs)
</div>

<h3>Worked Example 2: Moles to Particles</h3>

<div class="info-box">
<strong>Question:</strong> How many oxygen atoms are in 0.250 mol of O‚ÇÇ gas?<br><br>

<strong>Solution:</strong><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Convert moles of O‚ÇÇ molecules to number of molecules<br>
\[N_{\text{molecules}} = n \times N_A = 0.250 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} = 1.51 \times 10^{23} \text{ molecules}\]<br>

<strong>Step 2:</strong> Each O‚ÇÇ molecule contains 2 oxygen atoms<br>
\[N_{\text{atoms}} = 1.51 \times 10^{23} \times 2 = 3.02 \times 10^{23} \text{ atoms}\]<br>

<strong>Answer:</strong> \(3.02 \times 10^{23}\) oxygen atoms
</div>

<div class="y12-banner">
<div class="y12-icon">üî¨</div>
<div class="y12-content">
<strong>Module 8 Connection: Precision in Analytical Chemistry</strong>
<p>In gravimetric analysis, you'll precipitate ions and weigh them. If you miscount significant figures when converting mass ‚Üí moles ‚Üí particles, your percentage purity calculation will be incorrect. The HSC marking criteria penalize sig fig errors consistently.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<div class="card">
<div class="card-header">
<div class="card-icon">‚öõÔ∏è</div>
<h2>Atoms, Molecules, and Formula Units</h2>
</div>

<p>
Different substances require different terminology:
</p>

<div class="table-wrap">
<table>
<tr>
<th>Type</th>
<th>Term Used</th>
<th>Examples</th>
<th>Note</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Elements</strong></td>
<td>Atoms</td>
<td>1 mol Fe = \(6.022 \times 10^{23}\) atoms</td>
<td>Monatomic elements</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Molecular compounds</strong></td>
<td>Molecules</td>
<td>1 mol H‚ÇÇO = \(6.022 \times 10^{23}\) molecules</td>
<td>Covalent bonding</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Ionic compounds</strong></td>
<td>Formula units</td>
<td>1 mol NaCl = \(6.022 \times 10^{23}\) formula units</td>
<td>No discrete molecules</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td><strong>Diatomic gases</strong></td>
<td>Molecules</td>
<td>1 mol O‚ÇÇ = \(6.022 \times 10^{23}\) molecules = \(1.204 \times 10^{24}\) atoms</td>
<td>Two atoms per molecule</td>
</tr>
</table>
</div>

<h3>Worked Example 3: Counting Atoms in Compounds</h3>

<div class="info-box">
<strong>Question:</strong> How many total atoms are in 0.500 mol of calcium nitrate, Ca(NO‚ÇÉ)‚ÇÇ?<br><br>

<strong>Solution:</strong><br>
<strong>Step 1:</strong> Determine atoms per formula unit<br>
Ca(NO‚ÇÉ)‚ÇÇ contains: 1 Ca + 2 N + 6 O = <strong>9 atoms per formula unit</strong><br><br>

<strong>Step 2:</strong> Calculate number of formula units<br>
\[N_{\text{f.u.}} = 0.500 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} = 3.01 \times 10^{23} \text{ formula units}\]<br>

<strong>Step 3:</strong> Calculate total atoms<br>
\[N_{\text{atoms}} = 3.01 \times 10^{23} \times 9 = 2.71 \times 10^{24} \text{ atoms}\]<br>

<strong>Answer:</strong> \(2.71 \times 10^{24}\) total atoms
</div>

<div class="highlight-box">
<strong>‚ö†Ô∏è Common Error:</strong> Students often forget to multiply by the number of atoms per formula unit. Always count ALL atoms, including those inside polyatomic ions.
</div>
</div>

<div class="card">
<div class="card-header">
<div class="card-icon">üìè</div>
<h2>Why Use Moles Instead of Counting Particles?</h2>
</div>

<p>
Imagine trying to count individual atoms in a chemical reaction. For even a tiny reaction:
</p>

<div class="info-box">
<strong>Example:</strong> Burning 1 gram of carbon<br>
C + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí CO‚ÇÇ<br><br>

1 gram of carbon contains approximately \(5 \times 10^{22}\) atoms. It's impossible to count these individually, but weighing 1 gram is trivial. The mole allows us to "count by weighing."
</div>

<p>
The mole provides three critical advantages:
</p>

<ol style="margin-left: 20px; color: var(--text-muted); line-height: 1.8;">
<li><strong>Practicality:</strong> We can measure mass on a balance (macroscopic) rather than counting atoms (impossible)</li>
<li><strong>Stoichiometry:</strong> Balanced equations give mole ratios, not particle ratios</li>
<li><strong>Universality:</strong> The mole works for atoms, molecules, ions, electrons‚Äîany particle</li>
</ol>

<div class="y12-banner">
<div class="y12-icon">‚öñÔ∏è</div>
<div class="y12-content">
<strong>Module 5 Connection: Equilibrium Calculations</strong>
<p>In Year 12, you'll calculate equilibrium constants using molar concentrations: \(K_c = \frac{[\text{products}]}{[\text{reactants}]}\). Every concentration term is in mol/L. Without fluency in mole conversions now, equilibrium problems become impossible.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- COPY SECTION -->
<div class="copy-section">
<h2>üìã Copy into your books</h2>
<div class="copy-grid">
<div class="copy-item">
<h4>The Mole Definition</h4>
<ul>
<li>1 mole = \(6.022 \times 10^{23}\) particles</li>
<li>\(N_A = 6.022 \times 10^{23}\) mol‚Åª¬π</li>
<li>SI unit for amount of substance</li>
<li>Bridges atomic scale to lab scale</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="copy-item">
<h4>Key Conversions</h4>
<ul>
<li>\(n = \frac{N}{N_A}\) (particles ‚Üí moles)</li>
<li>\(N = n \times N_A\) (moles ‚Üí particles)</li>
<li>Always use 4 sig figs for \(N_A\)</li>
<li>"Equation First" rule applies</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="copy-item">
<h4>Terminology</h4>
<ul>
<li>Elements: atoms (Fe, C, He)</li>
<li>Molecules: H‚ÇÇO, CO‚ÇÇ, O‚ÇÇ</li>
<li>Formula units: NaCl, CaCO‚ÇÉ</li>
<li>Count ALL atoms in compounds</li>
</ul>
</div>

<div class="copy-item">
<h4>Year 12 Preparation</h4>
<ul>
<li>Mod 5: Moles ‚Üí concentration</li>
<li>Mod 6: Mole ratios in titrations</li>
<li>Mod 8: Moles in gravimetric analysis</li>
<li>Precision = HSC marks</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>

