<!-- EXTENSION -->
<div class="extension-card">
<h2>‚≠ê Extension Challenge</h2>

<p style="color: var(--text-muted); margin-bottom: 20px;">
These problems require university-level reasoning and integrate multiple concepts.
</p>

<div class="question-item" style="background: white;">
<p><strong>Challenge 1: Avogadro's Limit</strong></p>
<p>If you could remove one atom per nanosecond (\(10^{-9}\) s) from a 1-mole sample, how many years would it take to remove all atoms? Compare this to the age of the universe (\(1.38 \times 10^{10}\) years).</p>
<div class="answer-area"></div>
</div>

<div class="question-item" style="background: white;">
<p><strong>Challenge 2: Olympic Chemistry</strong></p>
<p>An Olympic swimming pool contains \(2.5 \times 10^{6}\) L of water (density 1.00 g/mL). Calculate:<br>
(a) Mass of water in kg<br>
(b) Moles of H‚ÇÇO (MM = 18.0 g/mol)<br>
(c) Total number of hydrogen atoms in the pool</p>
<div class="answer-area"></div>
</div>

<div class="question-item" style="background: white;">
<p><strong>Challenge 3: Year 12 Preview (Module 5)</strong></p>
<p>In equilibrium systems, concentrations are expressed in mol/L. If a 2.00 L flask contains \(3.011 \times 10^{23}\) molecules of N‚ÇÇO‚ÇÑ, calculate the molar concentration [N‚ÇÇO‚ÇÑ]. Explain why this unit is more useful than "molecules per liter" for equilibrium calculations.</p>
<div class="answer-area"></div>
</div>
</div>

<!-- ANSWERS SECTION -->
<div class="answers">
<div class="answers-header">
<div style="font-size: 32px;">‚úÖ</div>
<h2>Comprehensive Answers</h2>
</div>

<div class="answer-item">
<h4>üéØ ACTIVITY 01 ‚Äì Mole Magnitude</h4>
<p><strong>1.</strong> Mass = \((6.022 \times 10^{23}) \times 3.2 \text{ g} = 1.93 \times 10^{24}\) g = \(1.93 \times 10^{21}\) kg. Earth's mass = \(6.0 \times 10^{24}\) kg. The coins would be about <strong>320 times the mass of Earth</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>2.</strong> Volume of one grain ‚âà \(\frac{4}{3}\pi r^3 = \frac{4}{3}\pi (0.25 \text{ mm})^3 = 6.5 \times 10^{-11}\) L. Total volume = \((6.022 \times 10^{23}) \times (6.5 \times 10^{-11}) = 3.9 \times 10^{13}\) L, which is about <strong>70 times Sydney Harbour's volume</strong>.</p>
</div>

<div class="answer-item">
<h4>üß™ ACTIVITY 02 ‚Äì Conversions</h4>
<p><strong>Row 1:</strong> \(n = \frac{3.011 \times 10^{23}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} = 0.5000\) mol Ne</p>
<p><strong>Row 2:</strong> \(N = 2.50 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} = 1.51 \times 10^{24}\) molecules NH‚ÇÉ</p>
<p><strong>Row 3:</strong> Molecules CO‚ÇÇ = \(0.750 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} = 4.52 \times 10^{23}\). Each has 3 atoms, so total = \(4.52 \times 10^{23} \times 3 = 1.36 \times 10^{24}\) atoms</p>
<p><strong>Row 4:</strong> Moles NaCl = \(\frac{1.204 \times 10^{24}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} = 2.000\) mol. Since 1:1 ratio, <strong>2.000 mol Na‚Å∫</strong></p>
</div>

<div class="answer-item">
<h4>‚öõÔ∏è ACTIVITY 03 ‚Äì Complex Compounds</h4>
<p><strong>1. Al‚ÇÇ(SO‚ÇÑ)‚ÇÉ:</strong> 2 Al + 3 S + 12 O = <strong>17 atoms/f.u.</strong><br>
Total = \(0.500 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} \times 17 = 5.12 \times 10^{24}\) atoms</p>

<p><strong>2. CuSO‚ÇÑ¬∑5H‚ÇÇO:</strong> 1 Cu + 1 S + 4 O (from sulfate) + 10 H + 5 O (from water) = <strong>21 atoms/f.u.</strong><br>
Total = \(0.500 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} \times 21 = 6.32 \times 10^{24}\) atoms</p>

<p><strong>3. (NH‚ÇÑ)‚ÇÉPO‚ÇÑ:</strong> 3 N + 12 H + 1 P + 4 O = <strong>20 atoms/f.u.</strong><br>
Total = \(0.500 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} \times 20 = 6.02 \times 10^{24}\) atoms</p>
</div>

<div class="answer-item">
<h4>üè≠ ACTIVITY 04 ‚Äì Fertilizer Production</h4>
<p><strong>1.</strong> \(n = \frac{3.01 \times 10^{26}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} = 500\) mol NH‚ÇÉ</p>
<p><strong>2.</strong> N atoms: \(3.01 \times 10^{26} \times 1 = 3.01 \times 10^{26}\) atoms<br>
H atoms: \(3.01 \times 10^{26} \times 3 = 9.03 \times 10^{26}\) atoms</p>
<p><strong>3.</strong> Counting \(10^{26}\) molecules is impossible. The mole allows manufacturers to calculate mass from moles (\(m = n \times MM\)), then measure in tonnes using industrial scales. This bridges atomic-scale stoichiometry to practical manufacturing.</p>
</div>

<div class="answer-item">
<h4>‚ùì MULTIPLE CHOICE</h4>
<p><strong>1. C</strong> | <strong>2. C</strong> (12 O per f.u. √ó 0.250 mol √ó \(N_A\) = \(1.81 \times 10^{24}\)) | <strong>3. B</strong> (1 mol of anything = \(N_A\) particles) | <strong>4. A</strong> | <strong>5. A</strong></p>
</div>

<div class="answer-item">
<h4>üìù SHORT ANSWER</h4>
<p><strong>Q6:</strong> \(N = n \times N_A = 4.50 \times 10^{-3} \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} = 2.71 \times 10^{21}\) atoms</p>

<p><strong>Q7:</strong><br>
(a) \(n = \frac{9.033 \times 10^{24}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} = 15.00\) mol H atoms<br>
(b) Each H‚ÇÇ has 2 H atoms, so \(n_{\text{H}_2} = \frac{15.00}{2} = 7.500\) mol H‚ÇÇ</p>

<p><strong>Q8:</strong> Ca(NO‚ÇÉ)‚ÇÇ has 1 + 2 + 6 = 9 atoms/f.u.<br>
\(N = 0.350 \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} \times 9 = 1.90 \times 10^{24}\) atoms</p>

<p><strong>Q9:</strong> Individual atoms are too small to count directly. For example, burning 12 g of carbon (C + O‚ÇÇ ‚Üí CO‚ÇÇ) involves ~\(6 \times 10^{23}\) atoms. Using moles, we recognize 12 g = 1 mol C, allowing us to "count by weighing" on a laboratory balance.</p>

<p><strong>Q10:</strong> The precipitate mass (grams) must be converted to moles using \(n = m/MM\), then mole ratios from the balanced equation relate precipitate moles to original ion moles. Finally, convert back to mass for percentage calculation. Without the mole as an intermediate unit, mass ratios would vary with every substance pair.</p>
</div>

<div class="answer-item">
<h4>‚≠ê EXTENSION ANSWERS</h4>
<p><strong>Challenge 1:</strong> Time = \(\frac{6.022 \times 10^{23}}{10^9 \text{ s}^{-1}} = 6.022 \times 10^{14}\) s = \(1.91 \times 10^{7}\) years (19.1 million years). This is about <strong>0.14% of the universe's age</strong>‚Äîstill incomprehensibly long!</p>

<p><strong>Challenge 2:</strong><br>
(a) Mass = \(2.5 \times 10^{6} \text{ L} \times 1000 \text{ g/L} = 2.5 \times 10^{9}\) g = \(2.5 \times 10^{6}\) kg<br>
(b) \(n = \frac{2.5 \times 10^{9}}{18.0} = 1.39 \times 10^{8}\) mol H‚ÇÇO<br>
(c) H atoms = \(1.39 \times 10^{8} \times 6.022 \times 10^{23} \times 2 = 1.67 \times 10^{32}\) atoms</p>

<p><strong>Challenge 3:</strong> \(n = \frac{3.011 \times 10^{23}}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} = 0.500\) mol<br>
\([N_2O_4] = \frac{0.500}{2.00} = 0.250\) mol/L<br>
Mol/L is preferred because equilibrium expressions (\(K_c\)) use concentration ratios, not absolute particle numbers. Concentrations are intensive properties (independent of volume), making comparisons across different systems meaningful.</p>
</div>
</div>

